Here's the full migration. Your code has **four** Thread.Abort-related APIs that all throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are meaningless in .NET 8.

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;

        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just continue to finally and exit loop
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(2000));

        // If still alive after timeout, it will exit at its next checkpoint.
        // There is NO forcible kill in modern .NET — the code must cooperate.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

## What changed and why

| Original (.NET Framework) | Replacement (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitOne`, async I/O) — a `bool` cannot interrupt a blocked call |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown in .NET 8. The `when` guard avoids swallowing unrelated exceptions |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | Cooperative cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow — you simply continue or exit the loop |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Signals the token; every checkpoint sees it |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then Abort | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Blocks until the thread exits or timeout elapses — no forcible kill |

---

## Critical: Make `GetNextItem` cancellation-aware

This is the **most important pitfall**. If `GetNextItem()` blocks indefinitely (e.g., on a queue), `CancellationToken` won't interrupt it unless you pass the token through:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks forever, can't be cancelled
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER — wakes up immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If the blocking call doesn't accept a token (e.g., raw `Socket.Receive`), use `token.WaitHandle` as an alternative:

```csharp
// For APIs that don't accept CancellationToken
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { dataReadyEvent, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

---

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Cancellation isn't immediate** — it only fires at the next checkpoint (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`, a token-aware API, or the loop condition). Add checkpoints inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running.

2. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it's `IDisposable` and leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed. The `IDisposable` pattern on the class ensures this.

3. **No forcible thread kill exists in .NET 8** — if `GetNextItem()` calls uncooperative code you can't modify, the only escape hatch is to move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`.

4. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — the `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch your own cancellation, not someone else's.
